# .dockerignore — controls what is EXCLUDED from the Docker build context.
#
# WHY THIS MATTERS FOR BUILD SPEED:
# When you run 'docker build' or 'docker compose up --build', Docker first
# packages everything in the build context directory (.) and sends it to the
# Docker daemon. Without this file that includes:
#   .gradle/   — Gradle caches  (~200 MB)
#   build/     — compiled outputs (~300 MB of JARs and class files)
#   .git/      — git history     (~50 MB)
#   *.db       — local SQLite databases
#
# With .dockerignore these are excluded BEFORE the context is sent.
# Result: context goes from ~600 MB → ~5 MB, and Docker skips invalidating
# cached layers that have nothing to do with source changes.

# Gradle build outputs — rebuilt inside the builder container
**/build/
**/.gradle/

# Compiled Java class files
**/*.class

# Local databases created during Phase 1 / Phase 2 runs
*.db

# Git history — not needed to build or run the application
.git/
.gitignore

# IDE project files
.idea/
*.iml
**/.vscode/

# OS-generated files
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
